    <title>Palworld’s PS5 port is on hold indefinitely in Japan</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Screenshot from the Palworld PS5 launch trailer showing several of the game’s characters." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/9w9gS_Jm1kLRa7e7OYaPLMilTLc=/300x0:3540x2160/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73608384/videoframe_27627.0.png" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;Palworld&lt;/em&gt; | Screenshot: PlayStation (YouTube)&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="CYXPg9"&gt;Sony included the &lt;a href="https://store.playstation.com/en-us/product/UP6360-PPSA23126_00-0112788005082769/"&gt;PS5 launch of &lt;em&gt;Palworld&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;as one of its news items during &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24253137/playstation-ps5-state-of-play-september-2024"&gt;Tuesday evening’s State of Play presentation&lt;/a&gt;, but it left out a detail. While the game has launched on PlayStation platforms in 68 countries and regions worldwide, Japan is not one of them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="OdLkWl"&gt;The official Japanese account for the game &lt;a href="https://x.com/Palworld_JP/status/1838716479136763971"&gt;said on X&lt;/a&gt;, according to machine translation, that the release date in Japan “has not yet been decided,” without going into detail about the reason. It certainly seems like a reason could be &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/9/18/24248602/nintendo-pokemon-palworld-pocketpair-patent-infringement-lawsuit"&gt;the patent infringement lawsuit Nintendo and The Pokémon Company filed&lt;/a&gt; against Palworld developer Pocketpair last week, but the tweet didn’t confirm things either way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="G1yHxc"&gt;The &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/9/19/24248957/pocketpair-pokemon-patent-infrigement-lawsuit"&gt;most recent statement about the issue from Pocketpair&lt;/a&gt; is still &lt;a href="https://www.pocketpair.jp/news/news16"&gt;this one&lt;/a&gt; from...&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
